<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Draft:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Greater Manchester Combined Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (FD06)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fiscal devolution should be built </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around a new settlement between central</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> government based </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk and reward, whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h incentivises local investment -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> thereby rewarding growth and reducing dependency. This will enable places to develop greater self sufficiency and is crucial to ena</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble government to meet the financial challenges which lie ahead. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The devolution of substantial fiscal powers should be contingent on the ability of places to demonstrate the robustness of the functional economic area concerned and effective structures for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local leadership, decision-making and accountability for that area. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> warmly welcomes the CLG Select Committee Inquiry into fiscal devolution to cities and city regions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The inquiry is timely, following on from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">recommendations of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> the Silk Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">London Finance Commission,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> and responding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">launch of the City Centred Campaign for fiscal devolution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">advocated by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Core Cities Group, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Greater London Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> and London Councils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">We have argued </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">for many years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">that democratically elected local leaders need to have control over the levers and resources which impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on their ability to deliver economic growth and to improve the quality of life for local residents. It is essential that financial capa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">city is aligned with functional economic areas so that growth and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reform strategies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> integrated to support competitiveness and labour market productivity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in this country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which is one of the most centralised in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">world, limits local control over funding and means that cities are able to influence only around 5% of the taxes that are raised within them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">far less than international competitors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> constrain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s the ability of cities to deliver on growth and refo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rm. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The situation for major cities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is also out of step with moves to increase fiscal devolution to the devolved administrations. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst there have been a number of steps towards further devolution, in particular through City Deals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">forthcoming Growth Deals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">view these as only the beginning of an ongoing process of decentralisation from Whitehall. The City Deals process has underlined the importance of differential devolution, whereby packages of powers and resources can be devolve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d to local authorities based on the ability of those places to contribute to national priorities, as well as the capacity to demonstrate effective structures for local leadership, decision-making and accountability. One size does not fit all and devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of powers and resources may be through different packages and to different timescales. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recently published Core Cities Growth Prospectus</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> outlines the international evidence for decentralisation including fiscal devolution. The evidence shows tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cities with more local control over funding and policy achieve better economic results</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and are better placed to outperform the national economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is supported by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Professor Michael Parkinson’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">earch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">illustrates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that decentralising powers and resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coupled with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> spreading investment and encouraging high performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n a range of cities produce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s benefits on a national scale. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The case for change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> established the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">first statutory Combined Authority (GMCA) in the country, demonstrating the strength of local leadership and governance arrangements, and building on 25 years of joint working through the Association of Greater Manchester Authorities (AGMA). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">advantage of the Combined Authority model is the joint governance arrangements which it provides for transport, economic development and regeneration, which allow for strategic prioritisation of the levers of growth across the functional economic area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> GMCA works closely with the Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and together</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the GMCA and LEP provide a unique platform for governance and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accountability across the city region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for future devolution of powers and funding. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester’s econom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic performance has been strong over recent decades, even during the recession – generating £48billion GVA per annum (around 4%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the national economy), and whilst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the national picture remains uncertain, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e number of jobs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> predicte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d to grow by more than 7% over the next decade. However, while the economy has grown, our skills base and productivity have not kept pace and we have not been able to reduce dependency or close the gap between the tax that is generated here and the cost of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public services. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our productivity gap is in part due to lower skills levels and lower levels of economic activity than the South East and if we are to fulfil our growth potential we must address that gap. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite the reductions in funding to publi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services, total public sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spend in Greater Manchester increased from £21billion to £22billion between 2008/9 and 2011/12. Reductions in spend by local authorities, the police and fire services and others have been offset by increases in spending on wel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fare and health and social care. The cost of providing p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ublic sector services is becoming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increasingly unsustainable, with a greater proportion spent on the costs of dependency and less on opportuni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ties to increase growth and red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uce the demand for those se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rvices. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We know from our analysis and experience that with the right tools we can create jobs and growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth alone </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will not fundamentally change places or reduce the costs of dependency that fall to public services. We need to create </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">levers to drive both growth and reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which are</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rooted in real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">places with the capability and capacity to use them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This includes a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local skills agenda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will enable us to align the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">skills of our residents with jobs both now and in the future, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by enabling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more people to find sustainable work, productivity to rise and businesses to grow. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An example of our innovative place based approach is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater Manchester Work Programme Leavers scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This will provide integrated and intensive support to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">help people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">claiming Employment Support Allowance who have not found sustained work through the Work Programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seeking to create a platform for fiscal self-reliance tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> empowers local authorities to undertake their place shaping ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le to create high quality places that attract and retain more productive people and businesses. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our approach to achieving this, based around the twin themes of growth and reform, is set out in the recently revised Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester Strategy ‘Stronger Toge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ther’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the Greater Manchester Growth and Reform Plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> submitted to government as part of the Growth Deal Process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Incentivising and rewarding growth </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fiscal d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evolution should be built around a new settlement between central and local government based </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk and reward, whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h incentivises local investment -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rewarding economic growth and reducing dependency. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The aims of such devolution are to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">places </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">develop greater self-sufficiency with the tools to promote growth and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dependency to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">become </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">self-sustaining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the future. This is crucial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth and meeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the financial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> challenges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that lie </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ahead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for local government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">devolution of substantial fiscal powers should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contingent on the ability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">places </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to demonstrate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the robustness of the functional economic market area concerned and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effective structures for local leadership, decision-making and accountability for t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat area. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we have sought to harness central and local funds in new ways to support our growth priorities for many years. We have developed an Investment Fund that has allowed us to coordinate funds to deliver growth priorities across the city region with an emphasi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s on recyclable investment. We have also worked with government to develop the innovat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Earnback</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Model which allows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> us to capture a proportion of the growth generated as a result of our local investment in transport infrastructure for reinvestment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is based on a formula</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> linked to changes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rateable values over time at the Greater Manchester level, which provides a revenue stream over 30 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, provided that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> additional GVA is created relative to the agreed baseline. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This therefore provides an additio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nal incentive for Greater Manchester to prioritise local government spending to maximise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> growth. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We want to build on these approaches to drive long term growth through using new financial models that support early investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or projects whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">central and local government priorities converge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and for which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more traditional funding models </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do not work as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> central and local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work together to develop the optimum funding mechanisms to promote growth at the level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of place. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This must be accompanied by national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">modelling and forecasts for public sector spending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incentivise or account for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth in places.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The current system mitigates against innovation by treating local growth as a zero sum game – with growth in one locality being assumed to be at the expense of growth in another. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Fiscal measures</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fiscal devolution must play a significant role in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any realignment of the relationship between local authorities and central government. The current model rewards central government for behaviour and decisions made by local authorities, providing little incentive to communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local authorities do r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aise council tax locally, but the bandings are set nationally and central Government maintains significant control over the level of any council tax increases. Whilst the principle of council tax referendums provides direct accountability, the variable nat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ure of the referendum threshold set by central Government makes long term decision making for local authorities problematic.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council tax is only one property tax, and there is a strong case for others to be devolved to local authorities, such as stamp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> duty. Alongside retained business rates, local authorities would be incentivised to encourage economic activity such as house-buying in their area if they retained some or all of the stamp duty due on a property sale, and the funds could then be used to p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rovide local services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is also a need for a wider debate on local taxation, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in particular whether</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local authorities could be give</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n discretion to introduce other forms of taxation, for example a hotel room levy. Given the role local authoriti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es play in promoting their areas and encouraging both tourism and inward investment, a hotel room levy would provide a source of funding for such services derived from their success.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Public service reform </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As outlined above, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncentivising and rewa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rding growth must be accompanied by more control over the other public sector resources which are spent in local areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been on a journey of reforming public services which has involved piloting integrated working in the most deprive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d neighbourhoods of the city region, pioneering work on Troubled Families and the national whole place Community Budget Pilot. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our Community Budget Pilot has addressed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how to transform the way we deliver services in order to reduce dependency and demand, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd to increase productivity through work and skills. Our final submission to government included a number of new delivery and investment models which cross traditional public sector boundaries and have the ability to achieve improved outcomes through earli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intervention and prevention. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is part of a wider programme of Public Service Reform in Greater Manchester working on the reduction of demand and dependency – focusing on Early Years, Troubled Families, Transforming Justice, Health and Social Care an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d Work and Low Skills. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A priority for us is to take the results of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Community Budgets P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilot forward as the basis of a potential new settlement between national and local government that supports, incentivises and responds to public sector reform. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A new way of capturing the benefits of growth must also not solely be related to business rates as a proxy of growth, but should also be related to new investment models which are designed to deliver savings by reducing dependency. This can only be deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed on an individual place basis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Place based settlements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> strongly supports the proposal within the 2013 Autumn Statement for government to work towards local public services having the same long term indicative budgets as depart</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and supporting local areas to deliver services differently if the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y can show it will save money. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater certainty of future budgets would provide local partners with the impetus to invest now in public service reform that will deliver future savings.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> They will be able to decommission services no longer required in the knowledge that their investment will be recouped and recycled.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is strongly linked to the Greater Manchester Pub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic Service Reform approach, whereby we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are asking for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">freedom to reinvest the return on capital projects, and on the increased tax income as businesses begin to do better as a result, we are also focused on the need to keep the savings made in places from reduced dependency for long enough for those changes t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o people and places to become irreversible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Joint accountability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fiscal devolution is not just about whether powers should be devolved or remain at the centre. There are a range of policies and funding streams which need to reflect national and l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal priorities and where models of accountability could be explored in more detail. A solution may lie in creating a link between the channels of accountability already established by central government to manage its relationship with arms-length bodies, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the arrangements for local accountability in place in local government.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Local government finance reform</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although the focus of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inquiry relates to fiscal form it is also important to consider the wider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">context for local government fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite some changes to the local government finance system, local authorities are still heavily reliant on central government funding to fund services. The part-localisation of business rates was an attempt to remedy this, but the outcome from the proces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s was deeply disappointing as the incentive effect was heavily diluted, and overall funding levels remain determined by central government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst understanding and recognising the need for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Treasury to maintain control over public finances, there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also needs to be recognition within the funding system of the strong financial stewardship of local government, accompanied with a more trusting relationship between central and local. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prudential borrowing is a strong example of this, as it provides a fram</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ework within which local authorities can borrow what they need for capital purposes, and which provides some reassurance to Treasury regarding the affordability of such borrowing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The main sources of local funding are now both subject to direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment subsidy through the Council Tax Freeze Grants and the reduction in busin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ess rates following the Autumn S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tatement. Experience from the past shows that once local taxation loses its local rationale, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">danger that it loses credibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nment is faced with a fut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ure dilemma about whether to co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntinue with its subsidy or find another solution.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any reform of the wider local government finance system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must, at its core, retain the principle of equalisation, to ensure that there is an unde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rlying fairness within the system. A key element of this must be a reassessment of council tax, and in particular the bandings used. House prices have grown at significantly different rates across the country since the bands were originally set, and this h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as created an unequal system. Council tax bands must be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">revalued</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in a similar way to business rates assessments, to ensure that the tax being charged on a property is fair wherever in the country it is.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">8 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><a href="http://www.corecities.com/sites/default/files/images/publications/Competitive%20Cities,%20Prosperous%20People_%20Final%20Draft.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.corecities.com/sites/def</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ault/files/images/publications/Competitive%20Cities,%20Prosperous%20People_%20Final%20Draft.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.agma.gov.uk/cms_media/files/gm_strategy_stronger_together_full_report2.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.agma.gov.uk/cms_media/files/gm_strategy_stron</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ger_together_full_report2.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>